The majority of the apps you have on your phone are harmful to it. This is because many of them have been found to have viruses, and they can sometimes capture your personal information from your phone and transfer it to the app’s owners without your knowledge. If you don’t want to end yourself in a big situation, you should get rid of some of the risky apps listed below.
1. Optimization Applications
Application optimization isn’t always helpful for your phone. They sometimes do things that are completely unneeded, such as cleaning your cache. However, the truth is that most phones already have all of these features.
New versions of operating systems have been introduced that have these functionalities integrated in to the device, rendering optimizing programs in your phone completely worthless. All they do now is shorten your battery life by requiring some power for the cleaning cache activities.
2. Anti-virus software
Antivirus software that isn’t well-known is likewise a bad idea. There are viruses that masquerade as antivirus software. On your smartphone, certain antivirus programs run in the background and in the foreground. This means that more battery power will be allocated to these functions, resulting in lower battery efficiency. Furthermore, your smartphone will be slow.
3. Apps that use RAM
Apps that store and expand your RAM memory are likewise a rip-off. They can only clean your cache for a short period of time. There is no method to increase the RAM on your smartphone because it is fixed unless you purchase a completely new phone with extra RAM.
4. Apps for obtaining loans
Loan apps should not be kept on your phone because their owners have easy access to your personal information, such as phone contacts and texts. After you’ve received the loan, make sure you erase the apps from your device.


